<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the Coram Children’s Legal Centre (JRR 0038)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Coram Children’s Legal Centre</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Coram Children’s Legal Centre </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(CCLC) is an independent NGO working in the United Kingdom and around the world to protect and promote the rights of children, through the provision of direct legal services; the publication of free legal information online and in guides; research and poli</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cy work; law reform; training; and international consultancy on child rights. Founded in 1981, CCLC has over 30 years’ experience in providing legal advice and representation to children, their parents and carers and professionals throughout the UK. The CC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">LC’s legal practice specialises in education, family and immigration law and CCLC operates several free advice phone lines including the Child Law Advice Line</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and the Migrant Children’s Project Advice Line.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Migrant Children’s Project at CCLC provides s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pecialist advice and legal representation to migrant and refugee children and young people on issues such as age assessment and access to support and accommodation. As part of CCLC’s work to promote the implementation of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hildren’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rights, CCLC has underta</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ken amicus curiae interventions in a number of significant cases, including in the European Court of Human Rights, the Supreme Court and the Court of Appeal, providing assistance to the court on matters of children’s rights and best interests.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In this evi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ence, we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">focus on the impact of the proposals on children and young people’s access to justice and the incompatibility of the proposals with children’s human rights standards, including domestic, regional and international standards.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Standing</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The consultation paper asserts </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Government has identified approximately 50 judicial reviews each year between 2007 and 2011 that ‘appear to have been lodged by NGOs, charities, pressure groups and faith organisations’</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> through ‘a manual analysis of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> case level information’ which ‘is largely illustrative’ due to ‘uncertainties in recording and interpretation’.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> In our view t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">his is a wholly insufficient evidence base for the reforms to standing proposed.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The consultation paper states that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Government ‘is concerned that the wide approach to standing has tipped the balance too far, allowing judicial review to be used to seek publicity or otherwise to hinder the process of proper decision-making’</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and that this concern ‘is based on the principl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e that Parliament and the elected Government are best placed to determine what is in the public interest’.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">If a claimant were to initiate judicial review proceedings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> simply to ‘campaign against, frustrate or delay decisions’</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> this would undoubtedly be an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">improper purpose for judicial review, but in our view there is no evidence of such misuse, and none is provided by the Government in its consultation paper.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Every member of society has an interest in the lawful administration of executive power. The Gover</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nment should not seek to insulate itself from the accountability that judicial review </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">affords</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, including judicial reviews by those who are not directly affected which enable matters to be brought before the cour</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ts and ensure decision-makers can</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be called t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">account</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In particular, w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">concerned about </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">public interest cases that involve children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’s rights</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> issues</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. There will frequently be a wider public interest in cases that relate to children’s rights, and children are in many such cases uniquely unable to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> bring challenges for themselves, underscoring the particular importance of challenges brought by organisations that seek to protect children’s rights and welfare</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (see for example challenges brought by the Child Poverty Action Group and the Children’s Righ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ts Alliance for England)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. It would be a severely re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">trog</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ressive step </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for children’s rights </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">if the Government were to prevent their doing so.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Third party interventions</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is well </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">established</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by our most senior courts that third </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">party interveners should be a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ble to contribute their expertise in cases where to do so is in the interests of justice and the interest of the public. Lord Hoffman’s Opinion at </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">paragraphs 2 and 3  in the case of </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">E v The Chief Constable of the Royal Ulster Constabulary</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (Northern Ireland</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Human Rights Commission intervening) </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">[2008] UKHL 66, [2009] 1 AC 536</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> been adopted by the Supreme Court in its own Practice Directions</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14.4pt; margin:3pt 11.25pt 6pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">… In recent years the House has frequently been assisted by the submissions of statutory bodies and non-governmenta</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">l organisations on questions of general public importance. Leave is given to such bodies to intervene and make submissions, usually in writing but sometimes orally from the bar, in the expectation that their fund of knowledge or particular point of view wi</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ll enable them to provide the House with a more rounded picture than it would otherwise obtain. The House is grateful to such bodies for their help.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Recognising this, the Supreme </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Court</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> will not ordinarily make costs orders against </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">third</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> parties</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> same interests </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of justice </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are served by enabling and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">encouraging</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> third </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">parties to intervene</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> at the earliest opportunity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Court of Appeal, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">High Court and Tribunals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">his </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> not be stifled by restrictions that would make it harder and potentially </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">more costly, even unaffordable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for non-profit organisations to provide expert assistance to the court and the parties in cases of public interest.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> CCLC agrees with the submissions on these issues made by the Public Law Project.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">third </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">party</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> CCLC doe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s not join proceedings to support any of the parties</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> own cases, whether claimant or respondent. We seek to intervene where we consider that there may be matters of principle and interpretation of children’s rights engaged in particular proceedings irrespe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ctive of the parties</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> own interests, where our perspective as a specialist NGO could offer assistance to the court and all the parties. In the Supreme Court, CCLC’s assistance has been particularly welcomed in recent cases</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Hale L recently said the following of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">value of interventions:</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14.4pt; margin:3pt 11.25pt 6pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Once a matter is in court, the more important the subject, the more difficult the issues, the more help we need to try and get the right answer. ... No particular formality is required and t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">he invitation is a very open one, but not I think abused.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Commenting that ‘provided they stick to the rules, interventions are enormously helpful’, she noted specifically that ‘[o]</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ne</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> thing that interveners can do, which the parties may find it more diffic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ult and more costly to do, is to draw our attention to international jurisprudence which may be relevant to the issue’.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CCLC has always met its own costs in making </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">third</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> party interventions and to date has never claimed costs against any other parties to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> proceedings. Indeed, at the outset, prior to seeking the court’s permission to intervene we always make a written offer to undertake not to seek the recovery of our costs in return for similar protection from the other parties. This is a sensible and prac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tical arrangement which in our experience works well. The court has sufficient powers already to decide how to order or decline to order any party, including an intervener</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to pay costs or a contribution thereto, to the other partie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is no evidence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that we have seen to support the contention that interveners cause extra costs to be incurred. Indeed, the opposite is likely to be true. Given that our legal work is conducted at our own expense using in-house lawyers with pro bono assistance from counse</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l, volunteer researchers etc, it is arguable that the other parties and the court may actually be saved significant time and costs by adopting/accepting interveners’ own submissions and in bringing matters to the attention of the court (at our own expense)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that otherwise would either be omitted or left to the parties to prepare, particularly on public interest issues, leading to increased legal aid costs and increased government legal costs. Our experience is that our own intervention submissions have also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">led to concessions being made by the parties on key issues at large in the pleadings, which may otherwise still have remained in dispute, reducing argument and saving costly court and legal time. It is also realistic to say in light of interventions we hav</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e made in judicial reviews in the High Court in recent cases (for example, HC</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and SM</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">), that well prepared third party interventions ultimately reduce the likelihood of further appeals being pursued by either party, because the public interest issues and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">wider implications of the cases have been more thoroughly considered at the earliest opportunity, saving significant legal and judicial costs further down the line. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Judges already use their procedural powers and inherent authority to require interveners </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to comply with directions including tight schedules and marshalling arrangements to fit into the court’s established timetable for the case. It is not our experience that cases are delayed, or listings extended</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by interveners</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would agree with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">comments of Lord Justice Moses in the matter of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">HC v SSHD &amp; Commissioner of Police for the Metropolis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that early judicial directions and/or a case management hearing would assist in ensuring that cases involving additional parties are effectively timetable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d and marshalled</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f we were placed at any further increased costs risks than at present our ability to participate in cases of significance to the public interest would be seriously curtailed. We would still be able to intervene in the UK’s apex court </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">under its own rules, but effectively the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">risks in the High Court would prevent us becoming involved at the earliest stages, when matters of public importance could be resolved without giving rise to further appeals and in a cost efficient manner. Increasin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g risks on costs would be counter-productive and even increase the overall public cost of delivering justice. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Any measures that would increase the likelihood of non-parties being ordered to pay costs would be likely to have a chilling effect on NGOs’ cha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ritable fundraising particularly for those organisations where intervention and direct litigation work is a core aspect of their work,  and would be likely to reduce or prevent their participation in future cases. It would also deter other NGOs from contem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">plating involvement in cases where their expertise would be of value. At a time when eligibility for legal aid is more and more restricted, NGO interventions and actions are an increasingly necessary element in enabling access to justice and for issues to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be aired in judicial proceedings which would ordinarily have arisen within cases brought by individuals.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Costs</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We oppose the proposals to change legal aid payment for judicial review </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and the proposals on protective costs orders </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for a number of reasons</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">First, the Government has already rebalanced financial incentives when in April 2013 it introduced a fee for requests for an oral permission hearing and the removal of a right to an oral permission hearing where a claim is certified by a judge on the paper</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s as being totally without merit. The Government should first review the impact of this change before instituting further changes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Second, there are good reasons to have in place specific rules that protect claimants</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">from financial ruin if a judicial </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">review case is lost. This is about the nature of judicial review as a challenge by an individual against the state, and the inequality of power that exists. The Jackson review of 2009 made recommendations to protect judicial review claimants and ensure tha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t people are not deterred from bringing judicial reviews by the threat of very high costs if the case is lost. The proposals are not in line with the Jackson report, although no evidence is provided as to why his recommendations are not correct.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Third, th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e new proposal to allow a discretionary payment by the Legal Aid Agency does not correct the principal problem with the original proposal outlined in the Transforming Legal Aid consultation in April 2013, namely that transferring the financial risk to prov</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">iders – as the current proposal still does – will make providers unwilling to take on meritorious cases and the public, including children subject to unlawful actions by public bodies, will be without a remedy. Judicial review is a vital remedy for childre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n across all areas of law, and children will now be denied their right in law to challenge unlawful decisions, including decisions of considerable importance with safeguarding implications for very vulnerable children and young people.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Fourth, the propose</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d scheme creates a perverse incentive for lawyers to issue as soon as possible, because unless they issue, they do not have a chance of getting paid for the work they do preparing to issue. Once they have issued, there will be no incentive to settle and ri</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sk not getting the discretionary payment, as they will prefer the certainty of an order from the court to make their claim to the Legal Aid Agency. This will result in more cases being pushed to a permission hearing, increasing court time and costs. For ch</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ildren, any disincentive to settling cases is particularly problematic because of the negative impact of litigation on children.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The criteria </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for the discretionary payment </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are very complex. T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hey will require complex evidence to be provided to the Legal Ai</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d Agency and they will require a thorough assessment of this evidence by the Legal Aid Agency. We consider that it is unreasonable to expect providers to supply such evidence and we consider that the Legal Aid Agency does not have the capacity to consider </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it and, in our experience, expecting the Legal Aid Agency to do so will result in further delays adding to those that already exist in the consideration of applications. The scheme will be extremely onerous. In our view the merits of the case are best cons</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">idered by the Legal Aid Agency, as is done currently, at the start of the case. Moreover, if providers think they are unlikely to end up being paid the discretionary payment, they will still be deterred from taking cases on, leaving the public without the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ability to bring judicial reviews to challenge unlawful decisions by public bodies. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Procedural defects</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Government contended in t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he consultation paper that judicial review ‘can too often be used to delay perfectly reasonable decisions or actions’ and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that ‘[o]</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ften</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> this will be part of a campaign or other public relations activity and the judicial review will be founded on a procedural defect rather than a substantive illegality’.</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This position fails to recognise that a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> procedural defect is precisely t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he proper subject for judicial review. Substantive decisions may be examined in a judicial review only in so far as the decision is irrational.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rocedural safeguards and child-specific processes that have been put in place for children and young people </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are particularly important because of their inherent vulnerability and inability to challenge their treatment and experiences in administrative decision-making and processes.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> For example, consideration of the impacts of a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> proposed policy on children is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> especially important because of children’s inability to challenge such a policy once enacted.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The effect of challenges to procedural defects should not be characterised as simply costs or delays. On the contrary, such challenges in our experience often </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">demonstrate that following the proper procedure can and does often lead to a different outcome. For example, in the work of our Migrant Children’s Project we have seen cases brought on the grounds of a failure of the Home Office to comply with a procedural</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> requirement to attempt family tracing for unaccompanied asylum-seeking children. As shown by the case of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">KA (Afghanistan) &amp; Ors v Secretary of State for the Home Department </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">[2012] EWCA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Civ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 1014,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">failure of the Home Office to comply with its procedural dut</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ies could affect the outcome of children’s asylum cases.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The ‘no difference’ principle is about the courts second guessing what the outcome of a case would have been but for the procedural defect. The appropriate threshold is inevitability, i.e. that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">outcome would have inevitably been the same. If the threshold were lowered, this would require the courts to engage in a more detailed assessment of what outcome was likely or would have occurred and would therefore necessitate the court considering large </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">amounts of evidence on th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is and taking on a constitutionally inappropriate role in the assessment of executive decision-making.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Cases concerning procedural defects could be avoided through improved Government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">compliance with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">procedures and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">proper </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">decision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-making, and the earlier response of Government departments and public bodies to pre-action protocol letters.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Prompt and detailed Acknowledgement of Service by Government bodies mean that non-compliance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with a procedural requirement can be addressed as qui</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ckly as possible and cases can be resolved pre-permission. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Public Sector Equality Duty</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Judicial review has a vital role in improving the conduct of Government departments and public bodies, including on the question of whether these departments and b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">odies are complying with the Public Sector Equality Duty, and the possibility of judicial review can encourage compliance. Judicial review is, in our view, the appropriate remedy where the Government fails to comply with the duty. In addition, as recognise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d by the Government Equalities Office ‘Review of the Public Sector Equality Duty: Report of the Independent Steering Group’, the PSED may in many cases just be one grounds in the judicial review challenge, suggesting these judicial reviews would not fall a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">way.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Impact Assessment</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are concerned by the lack of a child impact assessment. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The government has an obligation, under the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child, to ‘undertake all appropriate legislative, administrative, and other measures for the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">implementation of the rights’ contained in the Convention,</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and to ensure that, in all actions concerning children, their best interests shall be a primary consideration. This fundamental principle applies whether the actions are taken by ‘public or privat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e social welfare institutions, courts of law, administrative authorities or legislative bodies’.</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This extends to the formation of government policy and legislation, and, according to the UN Committee on the Rights of the Child, child impact assessments ar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e key to fulfilling this obligation. The Committee stated, in its General Comment on ‘general measures of implementation’ that: </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14.4pt; margin:3pt 11.25pt 6pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Ensuring that the best interests of the child are a primary consideration in all actions concerning children (art. 3(1)), and t</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">hat all the provisions of the Convention are respected in legislation and policy development and delivery at all levels of government demands a continuous process of child impact assessment (predicting the impact of any proposed law, policy or budgetary al</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">location which affects children and the enjoyment of their rights) and child impact evaluation (evaluating the actual impact of implementation). This process needs to be built into government at all levels and as early as possible in the development of pol</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">icy.</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a></p><p style="line-height:14.4pt; margin:3pt 11.25pt 6pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14.4pt; margin:3pt 11.25pt 6pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14.4pt; margin:3pt 11.25pt 6pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Combined effects of the proposals with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">proposed residence test for civil legal aid</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The proposals for judicial review are even more worrying when seen in the context of previous cuts to legal aid and the further pro</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">posed restrictions to legal </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aid</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which are at varying stages of implementation. CCLC is particularly concerned about the proposed introduction of a residence test for civil legal aid. If such a test is int</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">roduced, thousands of children and </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">young people will be without redress and unab</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">le to assert their legal rights</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> across many areas of civil law, including public law, community care and education law</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. In </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">this context, it is even more important that public interest litigation by those without a direct interest is able to </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">play a role in </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uphold</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the rights of children and </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">challenging</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> violations of their rights or unlawful policy.</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Imposing a restrictive test for standing and making it more financially </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">risky</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for children’s organisations and others to bring li</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tigation would jeopardise this.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Equally, </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">past and ongoing cuts to civil legal aid increase the number of unrepresented claimants</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and claimants struggling to pay for private legal representation</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the need </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of the courts </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">expert assistance by third party interveners</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on points of pub</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lic interest may increase</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and seeking to curtail the ability of third parties to intervene in the public interest would be</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> an</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> inappropriate</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> step</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Combined effects of the proposals with appeals provisions in the Immigration Bill</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Immigration Bill </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">contains measures to drastically reduce appeal rights so that applicants will not be able to appeal on any grounds other than asylum, humanitarian protection and human rights. An appellant will no longer be able to appeal on the grounds that the Home Offic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e’s decision was not in accordance with the law. This will, for example, affect an unaccompanied asylum-seeking child who is unlawfully refused limited l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eave and will no longer be able to rely as a ground of appeal on the Government’s failure to comply wit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">h public policy as set out in the Immigration Rules or failure to comply with the child welfare duty under section 55 of the Borders, Citizenship and Immigration Act 2009.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">An applicant subject to a wrong decision by the Home Office </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">without a right of appe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">al </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ill have no</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> means of redress </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">other </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">than judicial review. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Financially </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disincentivising</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> legal aid providers from bringing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">what are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">meritorious judicial reviews</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> along with other measures that make judicial review less accessible as a remedy, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at the same </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">time as reducing judicial oversight of executive decision-making</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, diminishes access to justice and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">increases the likelihood of violations of children’s rights.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:C